The 'not null' option specifies that a local variable or parameter can be null, which can be useful when implementing business rules in OpenROAD. For example, the following code generates an error if the value of $custid is null:
      if (null($custid)) {
        raise_error("custid is required", "error_no_customer_specified");
      }

With the with keyword, you can specify null or a literal for the default value of a local variable or parameter. System constants are not allowed. The following examples demonstrate how to use the with keyword to assign default values:
     integer myvar = 10;
     float myvar = with default;
     real myvar = with null;
